{"parse":{"title":"Community Programme Unit","pageid":13506040,"revid":683239013,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>\n\nThe <b>Community Programme Unit</b> was established by the <a href=\"/wiki/BBC\" title=\"BBC\">BBC</a> to help members of the public create programmes to be broadcast nationally.\n</p><p>The unit was set up in 1972 by influential producers such as <a href=\"/wiki/Rowan_Ayers\" title=\"Rowan Ayers\">Rowan Ayers</a> having won the approval of the Director of Programmes <a href=\"/wiki/David_Attenborough\" title=\"David Attenborough\">David Attenborough</a> for a series of ten programmes called <i><a href=\"/wiki/Open_Door_(BBC_TV)\" title=\"Open Door (BBC TV)\">Open Door</a></i> for <a href=\"/wiki/BBC_Two\" title=\"BBC Two\">BBC 2</a>.  The first programme was broadcast on 2 April 1973.\n</p><p><i>Open Door</i> evolved into <i><a href=\"/wiki/Open_Space_(BBC_TV)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Open Space (BBC TV)\">Open Space</a></i> which by the end of the 1980s was receiving up to twenty proposals from the public for programmes every week. These proposals were evaluated by the CPU's staff three or four times a year and a <a href=\"/wiki/Shortlist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Shortlist\">shortlist</a> of six to eight potential programmes to fill the next series was drawn up. The programmes would usually highlight a group or point of view that was under-represented or misrepresented in British broadcasting,\n</p><p>With the increased availability and quality of domestic <a href=\"/wiki/Camcorder\" title=\"Camcorder\">video equipment</a> the CPU started compiling and broadcasting a series of <i> <a href=\"/wiki/Video_Diaries\" title=\"Video Diaries\">Video Diaries</a></i> which in turn evolved into <i><a href=\"/wiki/Video_Nation\" title=\"Video Nation\">Video Nation</a></i>.\n</p><p>The <b>Community Programme Unit</b> suffered from the budget cuts at the BBC and had been disbanded by 2004.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Community_Programme_Unit&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://mwg.org/portal/fredjohnson/media/pdf/fjohnson_vox_pop.pdf\">Vox Pops \u2013 The BBC\u2019s Community Programme Unit</a> \u2013  Fred Johnson</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Community_Programme_Unit&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.bectu.org.uk/news/bbc/nb0232.html#response\">Massive cuts announced at BBC</a> \u2013 <a href=\"/wiki/Broadcasting,_Entertainment,_Cinematograph_and_Theatre_Union\" title=\"Broadcasting, Entertainment, Cinematograph and Theatre Union\">BECTU</a> report</li></ul>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:BBC_Portail.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/BBC_Portail.svg/40px-BBC_Portail.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"22\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/BBC_Portail.svg/60px-BBC_Portail.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/BBC_Portail.svg/80px-BBC_Portail.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"90\" data-file-height=\"50\" /></a></td><td><i>This BBC Television-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.p